{
  "query": "When restoring grasslands, how do the outcomes of simply disturbing the soil before seeding compare to removing the topsoil entirely?",
  "relevant_summary": "Evidence from multiple studies shows that both soil disturbance and complete topsoil removal can enhance grassland restoration outcomes, but topsoil removal appears to provide more consistent benefits. A replicated, randomized, paired, controlled study in the UK (action 3415) found that removing turf before sowing seeds increased both grass and forb species richness in most cases compared to simply disturbing the soil before sowing. Topsoil removal also showed additional benefits including increased plant community similarity to intact steppe, enhanced species richness of sown plants, and improved seedling survival rates (3415). However, soil disturbance alone also showed some positive effects, such as increased abundance or species richness of specialist and generalist plant species (1728) and increased heathland plant numbers when combined with spreading heathland plant clippings (1711). Both approaches can reduce unwanted species - topsoil removal reduced cover of perennial rye-grass (1711) and common knapweed (3415), while soil disturbance reduced wavy hair grass cover (1685). The choice between methods may depend on specific restoration goals and site conditions, with topsoil removal showing more consistent positive outcomes but potentially requiring more intensive management.",
  "action_ids": [
    "1711",
    "3415",
    "1728",
    "1685"
  ]
}

