{
  "query": "How do the effects of sowing parasitic plants differ across European countries for restoring grassland vegetation?",
  "relevant_summary": "Sowing parasitic plants has been studied across several European countries with varying effects. Six studies examined this approach - four in the UK, one in Switzerland, and one in Belgium. The effects showed some consistency across countries: five of six studies found that sowing parasitic plants (yellow rattle, European yellow rattle, or marsh lousewort) increased plant species richness and/or diversity, including studies in the UK, Switzerland, and Belgium. In the UK specifically, studies found that sowing yellow rattle led to decreased total plant biomass in three of four studies. In Belgium, sowing marsh lousewort seeds increased the abundance of six target plant species. Swiss studies showed that European yellow rattle decreased grass cover but did not alter forb cover. UK research demonstrated that yellow rattle establishment helped other target meadow species colonize and resulted in more plant species being present when yellow rattle was established.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3404",
    "129",
    "133"
  ]
}

