{"summary": "Based on the evidence from action documents, several management practices have been shown to affect plant survival in grassland restoration when combined with seeding or planting. Planting grassland plants directly (action 3399) resulted in 44% of new seedlings surviving over four months, and combining planting with seeding increased the number of both total plant species and native plant species compared to seeding alone. 

Using nurse plants alongside seeding or planting (action 3402) showed mixed results for plant survival - one study found increased survival of planted plants when grown under nurse plants, while another found that any initial survival benefit disappeared after 2-3 years. Adding mulch before or after seeding/planting (action 3405) showed variable effects, with one study finding increased seed germination in most cases, and another finding that adding mulch after planting native prairie plants did not alter the growth of any of seven plant species.

Timing of management interventions appears crucial for plant survival, as studies examining grazing at different times (action 2291) found differences in plant survival between plots grazed at different times in some comparisons. For maintaining established grasslands, traditional management practices including mowing and grazing have been shown to affect plant communities, with some studies finding that extensively managed semi-natural grasslands (through light grazing or annual mowing) can support higher species richness and abundance of plants compared to intensively managed areas.", "query": "What management practices, when combined with seeding or planting, have been shown to affect the survival of new plants in grassland restoration?", "action_ids": ["3399", "3402", "3425", "2291", "3908", "133", "3945"]}

