{
  "query": "Which site preparation techniques appear most effective at increasing species richness before seeding in European grasslands?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on European grassland restoration studies, several site preparation techniques show effectiveness for increasing species richness before seeding. Soil disturbance before seeding, such as rotovating, has been found to increase both grass and forb species richness compared to lighter disturbance methods like harrowing (action 3413). Adding sulphur to soil before seeding showed mixed results, with one UK study finding it reduced plant species richness and vegetation cover (action 3428). Sowing seeds of parasitic species like yellow rattle has been shown to effectively increase plant species richness and diversity across five of six European studies (action 3404). For overall species-rich grassland restoration, effective techniques included in combination: grazing, introducing plant species, hay spreading and mowing (action 133). The evidence suggests that mechanical soil disturbance combined with sowing appropriate seed mixes, including parasitic species where suitable, provides the most consistent approach for increasing species richness in European grassland restoration projects.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3413",
    "3428",
    "3404",
    "133"
  ]
}

