{
  "query": "What evidence exists for the effectiveness of altering seed mix characteristics, such as density or species diversity, for grassland restoration in the USA?",
  "relevant_summary": "Evidence from multiple studies in the USA demonstrates varying effectiveness of altering seed mix characteristics for grassland restoration. \n\nIncreasing species diversity in seed mixes: Four USA studies found mixed results. Two replicated, controlled studies showed that increasing species richness in seed mixes increased the species richness of sown plants. However, one replicated site comparison study found no change in overall plant species richness when seed mix species richness was increased.\n\nIncreasing seed density: Four USA studies showed more consistent positive effects. One replicated, randomized, paired, controlled study found that higher seed density increased forb species richness. Another found that higher seed density increased grass cover and forb cover, while increasing purple needlegrass seedling emergence. One study also found that higher seed density reduced the cover of native grassland shrubs.\n\nUsing local seed sources: Two USA studies were conducted on this practice. One replicated controlled study found that vegetation cover increased over time when local seeds were sown compared to non-native seeds, while vegetation height did not differ. Another replicated, randomized, controlled experiment found no difference in plant survival when comparing local versus non-local Sandberg bluegrass varieties.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3406",
    "3405",
    "3400"
  ]
}

