{
  "query": "What are the documented impacts of sowing grass seeds on the abundance of native forbs and shrubs in North American grasslands?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on studies from North American grasslands, sowing grass seeds has shown several documented impacts on native forbs and shrubs. In studies of sowing native grass and forbs (action 3432), three of four replicated, randomized, controlled studies in the Czech Republic and the USA found that sowing native grass and forb seeds increased the cover or density of forb species. However, studies of sowing grass seeds alone (action 3397) showed negative impacts: two replicated studies in the USA and Canada found that sowing grass seeds reduced the abundance of native forb species in one study, while the other found no change in native forb density. For shrubs specifically, two replicated studies in the USA and Canada found that sowing grass seeds reduced the abundance of shrub species. Additionally, when examining sowing seeds at higher density (action 3405), one site comparison study in the USA found that sowing grass seeds at higher density reduced the cover of native grassland shrubs. These findings suggest that while sowing a mix of native grasses and forbs can benefit forb abundance, sowing grass seeds alone tends to have neutral to negative effects on native forb and shrub abundance in North American grasslands.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3432",
    "3397",
    "3405"
  ]
}

